
# --- TDD harness ---
# State is machine-written and local: it records where THIS checkout stands mid-cycle.
# Committing it makes every pull a merge conflict over a timestamp.
.claude/state/

# Built projects are their own repos with their own remotes. link_projects.sh clones them.
projects/

# PROGRESS.md is NOT ignored, deliberately. CLAUDE.md tells you your reviewer is an interviewer
# reading this repo on GitHub, and lists the board in the layout — so hiding it left the one
# artifact that shows the discipline as the one artifact that did not ship. It is generated, but so
# is a lockfile. Regenerate it before you commit (`harness.py status --write`); hand-editing it is
# how a board starts lying.
#
# HANDOFF.md is ignored, and the difference is in the code rather than in taste: it stamps the time
# into its own header on every render, so it is dirty after every run whether or not anything
# changed. It is also addressed to the next session rather than to a reader. `status` writes no
# timestamp — only one of the two carries information at the rate it changes.
HANDOFF.md

# A local bundle can carry .env credentials into a commit.
*.zip

# Byte-cache and cache dirs the harness itself creates: `init.sh` runs the vendored suite under
# .claude/, so these appear on the first verification run of a repo that may contain no Python of
# its own. A reviewer reading this repo should not be reading a committed __pycache__.
__pycache__/
*.pyc
.pytest_cache/
